value.0:
From within the age-tarnished bars of this golden cage, ghostly sounds of what must once have been a living inhabitant can be heard. 

You see a tag hanging from the cage, but whatever was written on it has long since faded away.

A dust-covered placard identifies this as an "Oracle Stone". Whatever description used to be written below is too faded to read. So is the tag attached to it.

It was probably just a carnival attraction anyway.

A plaque attached to this stone carving identifies it as an "easy path to godliness". Whatever else the plaque once said is obscured by rust. 

Of course, the runes are like nothing you've ever seen. More than likely, it's just gibberish. Though the attached tag is as unreadable as the carving itself, you've no doubt it had an exhorbitantly high price as a collectors piece.

You've no doubt that this book likely once contained a myriad of powerful spells and enchantments, just as the small descriptive card states it does.

But the ages have not been kind to the unprotected pages. Or to the tag listing its price, which is wholly unreadable.

The tiny descriptive plaque attached to the frame informs you that this is a first-hand depiction of some major war from countless ages ago. 

Unfortunately, to your eyes, it's more a first-hand depiction of a blank slate, the paint long since having faded to nothing. 

Much like the tag hanging from it. Too bad.

Welcome to The Emporium!

Wipe your feet before you enter, and don't touch anything you can't afford.
